Lab 7: Spatial Autocorrelation & Spatial Weights

Introduction

The data that well be working with for this lab comes from the open POLITY IV dataset. The Polity data series is a widely used data series in political science research. The latest version, Polity IV, contains coded annual information on the level of democracy for all independent states with greater than, \(500,000\) total population and covers the years \(18002014\). Politys conclusions about a states level of democracy are based on an evaluation of that states elections for competitiveness and openness, the nature of political participation in general, and the extent of checks on executive authority. For each year and country, a Polity Score is determined which ranges from -10 to +10, with -10 to -6 corresponding to autocracies, -5 to 5 corresponding to anocracies, and 6 to 10 to democracies. There are certainly limitations to using such a score to quantify democraticness, but for the purposes of this lab, this dataset will do just fine!

The primary goal of this lab is an initial exploration of the spatial analysis tools available in R. For starters, well do some basic choropleth mapping, and then well progress to developing spatial weights matrices and computing some spatial autocorrelation statistics. The actual lab exercise requires you to do a lot of exploration on your own, but this lab prep should get you started on your way! To start, were going to be relying on a number of spatial (and aspatial) packages to get our work done in R:

library(maptools) # Tools for mapping
library(rgdal)    # Reading and writing geographic data
library(stringr)  # Working with strings
library(ggplot2)  # Plotting and stuff
library(ggthemes) # Some nice themes, including the theme_map
library(plyr)     # The join fuction and others

This is a SpatialPolygonsDataFrame, which is a spatial variant of a data.frame. It has a bunch of generic functions specified for it, including things like summary() above, and even a base plot() function (though the base plot isnt that pretty):

plot(map)

Here is a CSV file that contains the latest Polity data. Normally this comes as an excel file, but since excel is a pain in R Ive done the conversion for you:

polity = read.csv("data/p4v2014.csv")
names(polity)
##  [1] "cyear"    "ccode"    "scode"    "country"  "year"     "flag"

Well start by subsetting for the year 2010, which is a year with particularly good coverage:

polity = subset(polity, year == 2010)

Since there are some missing values here, we need to drop (set to NA) some cases where the Polity variable isnt in the range -10 to +10:

polity$polity[polity$polity < -10] = NA

We can now join the Polity data to our global map using the ccode variable that they have in common. The plyr library has a nice function called join that does just this, and it does it in a way that is condusive to joining tabular data to spatial data:

# We have to be careful here, we're (re)assigning the tabular data for our global map
map@data = join(map@data, polity, by="ccode")

At this point, you can save this joined data to a new shapefile (if you want):

map$country = NULL  # There are duplicates in this column that muck things up...
writeOGR(map, 'data/polity_iv_map.shp', layer="polity_iv_map", driver="ESRI Shapefile")

Lets make a map

We can start plotting the Polity scores right away using the default spatial plotting function. This is spplot from the sp package, which is the main package for working with geographic data. However, we can do a lot nicer job if we use ggplot!

dem.palette = colorRampPalette(c("darkblue", "lightblue"), space = "rgb")
spplot(map, "polity", col.regions=dem.palette(20), 
       main="Polity IV Democracy Scores (2010)",
       sub="Darker = More authoritarian | Lighter = More democratic")

So lets try that again using ggplot. It requires a little extra work up front, but the results can be quite a bit nicer In particular, since ggplot expects everything to be a data.frame, we need to use the fortify function to convert the spatial data into a regular data.frame:

# This is a bit of a 'hack' to match up the attributes to the polygons
# In some cases, you might not need to do this, but sometimes its required :(
map@data$id <- as.numeric(rownames(map@data))-1

class(map)  # Not a regular data.frame...
## [1] "SpatialPolygonsDataFrame"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "sp"
new_map = fortify(map)
class(new_map)  # Now we have a regular data.frame!
## [1] "data.frame"

If you look at the head() of the new_map object, youll notice all the attribute information has been dropped. Again, a perculiarity of the fortify function. We can put things back with:

new_map = join(new_map, map@data, by="id")

Now plotting is just like we would for any other ggplot, with two key requirements:

  1. x and y have to be long and lat
  2. we need to use the group variable that fority has automagically created for us
p = ggplot(data=new_map, aes(x=long, y=lat, group=group))

p = p + geom_polygon(aes(fill=polity)) +
        geom_path(color="white") +
        coord_equal() +
        scale_fill_continuous("Polity Score") +
        labs(x="Longitude", y="Latitude",
             title="Polity IV Democracy Scores (2010)")
p

Even better, why dont we project this using a area-preserving projection; one of my favorites is Mollweid:

# First, let's create a bounding box to plot as the background...
outline = bbox(map)  # This grabs the bounding box of the overall map area
# However, we want a 'bounding box' of the whole globe:
outline = data.frame(xmin=-180, xmax=180, ymin=-90, ymax=90)

Next, well plot with the Mollweide projection:

p + geom_rect(data=outline, aes(xmin=xmin, xmax=xmax,
                                ymin=ymin, ymax=ymax,
                                x=NULL, y=NULL, group=NULL), 
              color="darkgrey", fill="transparent", size=0.3) +
    coord_map("mollweide") +
    theme_map()

Spatial Weights

In this section, were going to start building various spatial weights definitions, and calculate the associated spatial weights matrices. This is a neccesary step in quantifying spatial autocorrelation: defining what is meant by close or neighbor.

Contiguity

First, well start by defining neighbors as those countries that share boundaries this is called contiguity weights or contiguity neighbors. In this sense, countries that shared a boundary are considered neighbors. Note that for this exercise, were working with geographic (lat/long) data. Well need to spdep package to compute weights matrices:

library(spdep)
# Contiguity Neighbors (no snap distance)
W_cont = poly2nb(map, queen=TRUE)  # Google queen contiguity to learn what this means...
# Don't forget to try `?nb2list2` to figure out what's going on here...
W_cont_mat = nb2listw(W_cont, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

# Contiguity Neighbors (snap distance = 5 arc degrees)
W_cont_s = poly2nb(map, queen=TRUE, snap=5)
W_cont_s_mat = nb2listw(W_cont_s, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)

Now we can plot the connections (neighbor relations) using base R graphics. Since well want to plot connections based on the centroids of the polygons, well grab this information using the following snippet of code:

map_crd = coordinates(map)  # Get reference to map (centroid) coordinates

And now we plot!

plot(map, border="grey")
plot(W_cont_mat, coords=map_crd, pch=19, cex=0.1, col="blue", add=TRUE)
title("Direct Contiguity")

plot(map, border="grey")
plot(W_cont_s_mat, coords=map_crd, pch=19, cex=0.1, col="blue", add=TRUE)
title("Contiguity + 5 degrees")

Distance-based

Next, well load some data on the various capital cities of the world. Were doing this so that we can explore alternative definitions of close. For instance, were going to compute spatial weights matrices for both the centroids of the countries and their associated capital cities and compare the differences. Normally, it wouldnt be a good idea to compute distances in geographic coordinate space, but for the purposes of a demo, I think were ok When doing your own spatial autocorrelation analysis, it is important to think serious about what exactly close or nearby means!

cities = read.csv("data/global_cities.csv")

# Join the associated Polity attributes
cities = join(cities, map@data, by="ccode")

Now well upgrade the cities data.frame into a SpatialPointsDataFrame:

coordinates(cities) = c("long", "lat")
city_crd = coordinates(cities)  # Get reference to cities coordinates

K-nearest neighbors

Our first distance-based definition of close will be based on a specified number of near neighbors. We start with \(k = 1\), so that we only consider the closest country to be a neighbor. Normally this wouldnt be useful for spatial analysis (we need multiple neighbors), but its useful to explore:

# Centroids
W_knn1 = knn2nb(knearneigh(map_crd, k=1))
W_knn1_mat = nb2listw(W_knn1)

# Capitals
W_knn1_2 = knn2nb(knearneigh(city_crd, k=1))
W_knn1_mat_2 = nb2listw(W_knn1_2)

Plot the connections!

plot(map, border="grey")
plot(W_knn1_mat, coords=map_crd, pch=19, cex=0.1, col="blue", add=TRUE)
title("k=1 (Centroids)")

plot(map, border="grey")
plot(W_knn1_mat_2, coords=city_crd, pch=19, cex=0.1, col="blue", add=TRUE)
title("k=1 (Capitals)")

Heres an example of interpoint distance weights (i.e., connections between all nearby locations):

# Centroids
dist = unlist(nbdists(W_knn1, map_crd))
W_dist1 = dnearneigh(map_crd, d1=0, d2=max(dist)) 
W_dist1_mat = nb2listw(W_dist1)

# Capitals
dist_2 = unlist(nbdists(W_knn1_2, city_crd))
W_dist1_2 = dnearneigh(city_crd, d1=0, d2=max(city_crd)) 
W_dist1_mat_2 = nb2listw(W_dist1_2)

Plot the connections!

plot(map, border="grey")
plot(W_dist1_mat, coords=map_crd, pch=19, cex=0.1, col="blue", add=TRUE)
title("Minimum Distance (Centroids)")

plot(map, border="grey")
plot(W_dist1_mat_2,coords=city_crd, pch=19, cex=0.1, col="blue", add=TRUE)
title("Minimum Distance (Capitals)")

What about when \(k = 4\)?

# Centroids
W_knn4 = knn2nb(knearneigh(map_crd, k=4))
W_knn4_mat = nb2listw(W_knn4)

# Capitals
W_knn4_2 = knn2nb(knearneigh(city_crd, k=4))
W_knn4_mat_2 = nb2listw(W_knn4_2)

Plot the connections! Note: Were just doing this to see whats going on, this isnt something well do all the time

plot(map, border="grey")
plot(W_knn4_mat, coords=map_crd, pch=19, cex=0.1, col="blue", add=TRUE)
title("k=4 (Centroids)")

plot(map, border="grey")
plot(W_knn4_mat_2, coords=city_crd, pch=19, cex=0.1, col="blue", add=TRUE)
title("k=4 (Capitals)")

Sphere of Influence

Finally, how about all sphere of influence neighbors? I think this one looks the coolest

# Centroids
W_del = tri2nb(map_crd)
W_soi = graph2nb(soi.graph(W_del, map_crd))
W_soi_mat = nb2listw(W_soi)

# Capitals
W_del_2 = tri2nb(city_crd)
W_soi_2 = graph2nb(soi.graph(W_del_2, city_crd))
W_soi_mat_2 = nb2listw(W_soi_2)

Plot the connections!

plot(map, border="grey")
plot(W_soi_mat, coords=map_crd, pch=19, cex=0.1, col="blue", add=T)
title("Sphere of Influence (Centroids)")

plot(map, border="grey")
plot(W_soi_mat_2, coords=city_crd, pch=19, cex=0.1, col="blue", add=T)
title("Sphere of Influence (Capitals)")

Spatial Autocorrelation

When computing spatial autocorrelation, we could use any one of the above weights definitions. Here well use \(k = 4\), and ignore any countries without a polity score:

full = map[!is.na(map$polity),]
full_crd = coordinates(full)

Compute the weights matrices

W_knn4 = knn2nb(knearneigh(full_crd, k=4), row.names=full$ccode)
W_knn4_mat = nb2listw(W_knn4)

Plot the connections (for fun):

plot(map, border="grey")
plot(W_knn4_mat, coords=full_crd, pch=19, cex=0.1, col="blue", add=TRUE)

Global spatial autocorrelation

Well start by exploring Global Autocorrelation Tests. Morans I and Gearys c. Do these two tests confirm one another? I havent shown you Gearys c, so youll have to figure out how to do this one your own (and include it in your lab writeup).

moran.test(full$polity, listw=W_knn4_mat, zero.policy=TRUE)
## 
##  Moran I test under randomisation
## 
## data:  full$polity  
## weights: W_knn4_mat  
## 
## Moran I statistic standard deviate = 8.1517, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: greater
## sample estimates:
## Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
##       0.419434756      -0.006535948       0.002730663

And now its time to plot the Moran scatterplot. This is a staple of spatial autocorrelation analysis. Well talk about this more in class, but really, all were doing is plotting a variable, in this case polity, against its lagged version (the mean of the polity score for the nearest 4 neighbors):

moran.plot(full$polity, listw=W_knn4_mat, zero.policy=TRUE, 
           pch=16, col="darkgrey", cex=.5, quiet=FALSE, 
           labels=as.character(full$country), 
           xlab="Polity IV Metric", ylab="Polity IV Metric (Spatial Lag)", 
           main="Moran Scatterplot (k=4)")

## Potentially influential observations of
##   lm(formula = wx ~ x) :
## 
##              dfb.1_ dfb.x dffit   cov.r   cook.d hat  
## Belarus       0.35  -0.34  0.40_*  0.96    0.08   0.03
## China         0.03  -0.03  0.03    1.04_*  0.00   0.03
## Cuba          0.35  -0.34  0.40_*  0.96    0.08   0.03
## North Korea   0.32  -0.35  0.39_*  1.00    0.07   0.04

## Thailand     -0.15   0.00 -0.18    0.96_*  0.02   0.01
## Eritrea      -0.02   0.02 -0.02    1.04_*  0.00   0.03

The slope of the plot (the regression line) gives us a measure of the spatial autocorrelation in the polity variable! Very cool!

Local spatial autocorrelation

Now what about local spatial autocorrelation? For now, suffice to say that this is a local measure of spatial autocorrelation that gives us an idea of the level of spatial autocorrelation at each location in the dataset. Well spend a lot more time on this in future labs and lectures. For now, well compute the local spatial autocorrelation statistic

lm1 = localmoran(full$polity, listw=W_knn4_mat, zero.policy=TRUE)

and add it to our dataset so that we can map the local levels of clustering:

# Extract (absolute) z-scores and create new variable `lm1`
full$lm1 = abs(lm1[, "Z.Ii"])

Again, since everything has to be a data.frame for ggplot, well fortify the spatial data and add the full data attributes back:

# Match up the attributes to the polygons
full@data$id <- as.numeric(rownames(full@data))-1
full.plot = fortify(full)
full.plot = join(full.plot, full@data, by="id")

Now were able to map the local Morans Ii Z-scores:

p = ggplot(data=full.plot, aes(long, lat, group=group))

p + geom_polygon(aes(fill=lm1), color="grey") +
    geom_rect(data=outline, aes(xmin=xmin, xmax=xmax, ymin=ymin, ymax=ymax, x=NULL, y=NULL, group=NULL),
              fill="transparent", color="darkgrey") +  
    scale_fill_gradient("Moran's Ii\nZ-Score", low="white", high="red") +
    labs(x="Longitude", y="Latitude",
         title="Spatial Autocorrelation in Polity Scores (2010)") + 
    coord_map("mollweide") +
    theme_map()
